    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Of course, let's dive into the molecular details. Ibuprofen is a nonselective inhibitor of the cyclooxygenase (COX) enzymes, which exist in two main forms: COX-1 and COX-2. At the molecular level, ibuprofen binds to the active site of these enzymes, which is where arachidonic acid normally binds. The active site consists of a hydrophobic pocket that accommodates the substrate, and the binding of ibuprofen to this site prevents arachidonic acid from entering.\n\nCOX-1 is constitutively expressed in most tissues and is involved in the production of prostaglandins that protect the stomach lining and regulate platelet function. COX-2, on the other hand, is inducible and is primarily expressed during inflammation. Ibuprofen's nonselective nature means it inhibits both COX-1 and COX-2, but it has a relatively higher affinity for COX-2, which is why it is more effective at reducing inflammation and pain.\n\nThe binding of ibuprofen to the COX enzymes involves the formation of a hydrogen bond between the ibuprofen molecule and a serine residue in the active site. This interaction disrupts the normal catalytic activity of the enzyme, preventing the",
      "source": "target",
